Introduction¶

An introduction to the problem would go here. Motivate the problem. Why is this of interest?

In the recent political climate, there seems to have been a mix of politics and logical beliefs. Recent events have highlighted the partisan and political differences and divides on certain science and logic related issues. The COVID-19 outbreak, for example, highlighted the political divide in putting policies to control the COVID-19 virus. A Pew Research study had reported that Democrats were more likely than other parties to have a positive sentiment to vaccines and scientific research(Pasquini & Saks, 2022). Another example involved the overturning of Roe v. Wade which would allow abortion laws to be handled by the states, all of which are of different parties(Baker, 2022). And each party seems to hold different views on abortions. In this vein, government officials from each party seems to have differing opinions on logical structures in America. Therefore, I want to observe how the party an average American citizen chose relates to their logical beliefs. What is the trend or relationship between an average citizen's party and their logical beliefs? For this study, I will be using and analyzing a sample from the Cards Against Humanity, Pulse of the Nation dataset. I will be evaluating the Political Affiliation, Automation, Vaccines, Books, Ghosts, Climate Change, Scientists, Scientific Research, Federal Funding of Scientific Research, and Age variables. The Automation variables answers whether a participant believes that automation is likely or unlikely to replace humans in their jobs. Vaccines discusses whether a person agrees or disagrees about the benefits and safety of vaccines. Books discusses how many books the person read. Ghosts answers whether a person believes in ghosts or not. Climate Change discusses whether a participant believes climate change is real or not. Scientists evaluates whether a person believes that scientists are doing good for the public. Scientific Research shows how much the participant estimates the amount spent on research to be, in percentage. Federal Funding in Scientific Research evaluates whether a person thinks the funding for scientific research is About Right, Too High, or Too Low. I am using these variables as they describe a person's logic and belief on modern science or superstition. I am also going to compare them with the Political Affiliation table to see whether there is a pattern. The Political Affiliations in this study are Democrat, Republican, Independent, and DK/REF(Don't Know/Refused to Answer). DK/REF can be assumed to be undecided or they didn't answer what their party was. Age is also used since their ages could affect their life experiences which could affect their logical beliefs

Data Description¶

You might use some data descriptives here. The data should be clear to anyone who has not looked at the dataset. For example, make sure you indicate how many people there are, how many people in different groups if that is important for your project, and summary statistics of the variables you are looking at.

Overall, there are 310 people in this table. Of those people, 120 are Independent, 72 are Republican, 87 are Democrat, and 31 are DK/REF. The highest number and percentage of participants who said that it was likely that automation will replace humans in the workforce was for the Democrat group(23 participants, 38.33%). The lowest count was for DK/REF(7 people, 11.67%). The highest percentage of people who said that such an event is unlikely came from the Independent party(39.92%). The Independent and Democratic parties had higher percentages of saying "No" to ghosts being real but also saying "Yes." However, there were more counts for saying "No" for all parties than for answering "Yes." Therefore, it's more likely that regardless of political party, the belief of ghosts or paranormal phenomena was less likely. Democrats had very high counts for "Strongly Agree"(42) on their opinion that scientists were good for the nation. Democrats and DK/REF had the lowest count for "Strongly Disagree." Repbulicans were more likely to answer moderately, answering "Somewhat Agree" or "Somewhat Disagree." Independents were also highly likely in count to agree that scientists are beneficial. Democrats and Independents had the highest count and percentage of strongly agreeing or somewhat agreeing that vaccines are safe and beneficial. Republicans had the most counts and percentages for somewhat disagreeing. Although "Strongly Disagree" generally had a low count, Independents had the highest number. For climate change, the counts and percentages for DK/REF were equally split by 25%. Democrats were significantly more likely to answer that climate change is real and caused by people as most of them(69) answered this while only 5 democrats said it is "Not Real" and only 9 said "Real and Not Caused by People". In comparison, there were a higher amount of Independents and Republicans who answered that climate change was not real or real and not caused by other people. And there were significantly less Republicans who agreed that climate change was real and caused by people. A high number of democrats thought the funding for research was too low. Independents also had a high number for this answer but a majority of them also had a high number thinking it was about right. Republicans found the funding to be at the right amount.

Conclusion¶

Both parties are more likely to disagree that automation will replace human employees or that ghosts are real. However, there are more answers for agreeing about the automation event with Independents and Democrats than with other parties. And Democrats and Independents had a lot more answers believing ghosts weren't real then Republicans, showing a trend that Democrats and occasionally, Independents, were more likely to have stronger views on statements than Republicans. For example, on evaluating whether scientists are honest and good, Democrats and Independents were much more likely to choose "Strongly Agree," compared to Republicans who majorly chose more moderate answers. Majority of the Democrats answered that they thought that climate change was real and caused by people, compared to other parties who had more answers for other choices. In contrast, Republicans didn't have a high count for the answer that climate change was real and caused by other people. Democrats also thought that funding for research was too low and majority strongly agreed that vaccines were safe. Republicans on the other hand, mostly answered that the funding is about right and although most strongly agreed about the safety of vaccines, there were more answers disagreeing with this for Republicans than for other parties. Indepedents also strongly agreed that vaccines were safe but had more moderate answers than Democrats. And the age of the people in these political affiliations had no relationship with their logical background, from the books they've read to their guess on the amount of funding on research. An overall pattern between political affiliations of citizens and logical beliefs is that Democrats are more likely to have stronger logical beliefs and positions, especially strongly positive opinions on modern issues like climate change or vaccines. Although all parties agreed with science, Democrats and Independents agreed much more strongly about it. This information can be useful for voters since they can compare their logical beliefs with the trends of the political parties on certain stances and therefore, choose the party to vote for in their next election. This can also be useful for politicians to help their campaigns by finding out the trend for their party on certain logical stances. This can help create an outline to campaign from.
